4. Identify the company assets that may be at risk from a threat actor for the following types of institutions.
Remember: Each company will react differently in terms of the type of assets it is trying to protect.
Financial	The assets at risk are customers’ financial data (such as bank account details, credit card information, and transaction history), transaction systems, algorithms, trading strategies and financial models. 
Medical	The assets at risk are patient health records, data acquired thru medical research and medical devices being compromised or sabotaged.
Educational	The assets at risk are student and faculty personal data, research data the institution may have acquired, and online platforms used for learning.
Government	The assets at risk are classified information, infrastructure being interrupted (such as energy or transportation), and national security, defense and intelligence would be at risk.
Retail 	The assets at risk are customers payment information (such as credit card details), inventory management and customer loyalty program.
Pharmaceutical	The assets at risk are research data, drug formulas, information from clinical trials, and manufacturing processes possibly being interrupted.
Entertainment	The assets at risk are scripts, music, video content, customer data, and possible disruption of online streaming platforms.

